As long as the conductor gets the new code first (which should always be the case for major version upgrades) we'll be fine.

The concern is only if we backport this to a stable release, because for "minor" updates within the same release I'm not aware of any requirement to update controller-tier first, so compute hosts could conceivably end up running code that's not yet deployed in the conductor.

I think a decorator would be... fragile? As in, the local forbid-save-under-migration-context decorator needs to be called first, before the remotable decorator. I'm sure there's a way to achieve that, but I *think* it's done according to the order the decorators are called in, so if we flip two lines, we'd break stuff:

  @remotable
  @forbid_save_under_migration_context

Is not the same as

  @forbid_save_under_migration_context
  @remotable

